<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- TITLE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Getting Started
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        An overview of the Urban Chaos Light Editor interface, file controls, map view, layers, and lighting properties.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- OVERVIEW -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        The Light Editor
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Light Editor is used to create, edit, preview, and export Urban Chaos light files.
        Light files control both individual point lights placed on the map and the overall ambient
        lighting settings used by the level.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        A light file can be edited with or without a map loaded, but loading the matching map gives
        you the full visual context for where lights are placed, how far their ranges extend, and
        how the lighting will appear against terrain, buildings, and objects.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/getting_started_light_editor_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- STATUS BAR -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        The Status Bar
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        At the bottom of the window is the <Bold>status bar</Bold>. This provides immediate
        feedback about the editor state and recent actions.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,2">
        The status bar shows:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The <Bold>current status message</Bold>, such as whether a file has been opened, saved, or exported.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The <Bold>currently loaded map file</Bold>, if one is open.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The <Bold>currently loaded light file</Bold>, if one is open.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The current <Bold>X/Z map coordinate</Bold> under the mouse cursor.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/getting_started_status_bar.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- TOP BAR -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Top Bar &amp; Quick Actions
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The top bar provides fast access to the most common Light Editor actions. These shortcut
        buttons allow you to open map files, open light files, quickly save the active light file,
        toggle map layers, and launch the 3D viewport.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/getting_started_top_bar.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,10,0,2">
        Open Map
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Open Map</Bold> button loads an Urban Chaos map file so that lights can be
        viewed and edited in their correct world position. This can also be accessed from
        <Bold>File → Open Map</Bold>
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" FontSize="12" Foreground="#808080">(Ctrl+Shift+O)</Run>.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,10,0,2">
        Open Light File
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Open Light File</Bold> button opens an existing
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.lgt</Run>
        light file. This can also be accessed from
        <Bold>File → Open Light File</Bold>
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" FontSize="12" Foreground="#808080">(Ctrl+O)</Run>.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Automatic map loading:</Run>
                <Run>
                    When a light file is opened, the editor automatically looks for a map file with the same name.
                    If a matching map file exists, it is loaded automatically. If no matching map file is found,
                    no map is loaded and you can manually select one using the Open Map button or File → Open Map.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,10,0,2">
        Quick Save
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Quick Save</Bold> button saves the currently loaded light file in place.
        This overwrites the active
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.lgt</Run>
        file using the current editor values.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,0">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">⚠ Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Quick Save overwrites the currently loaded light file directly. Work on copies of original game files
                    if you want to preserve the unmodified versions.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- LAYER CONTROLS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Map View &amp; Layer Controls
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Light Editor uses a map view similar to the Map Editor. Individual layer buttons allow
        you to control which parts of the map are visible while working with lights.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/getting_started_layer_controls.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,10,0,2">
        Available Layers
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">Cell Textures</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Displays the ground texture cells from the loaded map file. This provides visual reference
        for placing lights onto streets, rooftops, interiors, alleys, and other map areas.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">Buildings</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Displays the building facets from the loaded map. This helps you position lights in relation
        to walls, fences, doors, ladders, and other structural features.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">Objects</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Displays prim objects from the loaded map. This is useful for aligning lights with objects
        such as street lamps, vehicles, crates, and other environmental details.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">Lights</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Displays each individual light entry on the map. This is the main editing layer for seeing
        where lights are positioned.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">Ranges</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Displays the area reached by each light. This helps you understand how far a light will
        affect the surrounding map and makes it easier to tune range values visually.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">3D View</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Opens the 3D viewport for previewing the map and lighting from a three-dimensional
        perspective.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- FILE MENU -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        File Menu
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The File menu contains the main commands for creating, opening, saving, and exporting
        light files.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/getting_started_file_menu.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">New Lights
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" FontSize="12" Foreground="#808080">(Ctrl+N)</Run>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Creates a new light file.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">Open Light File
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" FontSize="12" Foreground="#808080">(Ctrl+O)</Run>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Opens an existing
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.lgt</Run>
        light file.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">Open Map
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" FontSize="12" Foreground="#808080">(Ctrl+Shift+O)</Run>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Opens a map file manually. Use this when the editor cannot automatically locate a matching
        map for the currently loaded light file.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">Save
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" FontSize="12" Foreground="#808080">(Ctrl+S)</Run>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Saves the current light file in place.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">Save As
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" FontSize="12" Foreground="#808080">(Ctrl+Shift+S)</Run>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Saves the current light file to a new file location.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- EXPORT MAP -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,14,0,2">
        Export Map
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>File → Export Map</Bold> section allows you to export a PNG image of the map
        and selected lighting layers.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,2">
        You can export:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The <Bold>currently loaded map</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>One or more maps</Bold> selected from the file system.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        During export, you are prompted to choose which layers should be included and what image
        quality should be used.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,8,0,0">
        The Light Editor can also export light file statistics to a text file, including details
        such as the number of lights, the light file version, and the overall light settings.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/getting_started_export_map.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- MAIN DISPLAY TABS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Main Display Tabs
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The main editor display is divided into two primary tabs:
        <Bold>Lights List</Bold> and <Bold>Map Properties</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/getting_started_main_tabs.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- LIGHTS LIST TAB -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,10,0,2">
        Lights List
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Lights List</Bold> tab displays the currently active light entries in the loaded
        light file. Each row represents one light.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,2">
        The table shows each light's key properties, including:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The light's <Bold>position number</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Its <Bold>X/Z map coordinates</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Its <Bold>Y coordinate</Bold>, representing vertical placement.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Its <Bold>range</Bold>, from
                <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">0</Run>
                to
                <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">255</Run>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Its <Bold>RGB colour values</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                A <Bold>colour preview swatch</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Along the bottom of the Lights List are buttons for common light operations:
        <Bold>Add Light</Bold>, <Bold>Edit Light</Bold>, <Bold>Delete Light</Bold>,
        <Bold>Copy Light</Bold>, and <Bold>Paste Light</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/getting_started_lights_list.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- MAP PROPERTIES TAB -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,2">
        Map Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Map Properties</Bold> tab contains the overall lighting settings for the light
        file. These values affect the general appearance of the level and work together with
        individual light entries.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/getting_started_map_properties.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- FLAGS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,10,0,2">
        Light Flags
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Map Properties tab includes three main flags:
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">Night Enabled</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Enables night-time lighting. This is disabled by default. In Urban Chaos, enabling night
        also means that the map is treated as raining.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">Lamps On</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Enables light-emitting prims, such as street lamps and similar objects.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,6,0,1">Darken Walls</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Darkens the lower part of facet textures slightly, giving walls more depth and contrast.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- AMBIENT / D3D / SPECULAR / PRIM LIGHTING -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,14,0,2">
        Ambient Lighting
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Ambient</Bold> is the overall colour filter for the light file. It can be thought of
        like a movie camera filter applied across the level. You can set the RGB values manually,
        and the editor displays a preview swatch below the controls.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,2">
        D3D Colour
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>D3D Colour</Bold> is the supporting ambient light colour used by the renderer.
        Like Ambient, it uses RGB values and includes a preview swatch so you can quickly see the
        selected colour.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,2">
        Specular Colour
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Specular Colour</Bold> controls highlight lighting on the map. This value includes
        an Alpha channel as well as RGB channels. A preview swatch is shown to help visualise the
        selected highlight colour.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,2">
        Prim Lighting
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Prim Lighting</Bold> controls the colour of lights emitted by light-producing prims,
        such as street lamps. This can be set to any RGB colour and previewed using the colour swatch.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,2">
        Night Sky Colour
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Night Sky Colour</Bold> is an unused legacy feature. Before
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">sky.tga</Run>
        was implemented, this value represented the colour used for the sky box.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Use the preview swatches as a quick way to compare colour choices before saving the light file.
                    For the final result, use the map view or 3D viewport to judge how the values work together.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- PREVIEW D3D LIGHTING -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,14,0,2">
        Preview D3D Lighting
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Preview D3D Lighting</Bold> button provides a quick at-a-glance comparison of
        how the ambient lighting values will alter the appearance of a normal building on the map.
        This is useful when tuning the general mood of a level before placing or adjusting individual
        lights.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/Urban%20Chaos%20Light%20Editor;component/Help/Images/getting_started_preview_d3d_lighting.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- NEXT STEPS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Next Steps
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Once you are familiar with the Light Editor interface, continue to the next help topics:
        <Bold>Adding &amp; Editing Lights</Bold>, <Bold>Map Properties</Bold>, and
        <Bold>Using the 3D Preview</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        A good starting point is to open an existing game light file, allow the editor to load the
        matching map automatically, and then inspect how the original levels use ambient settings,
        point lights, light ranges, and light-emitting prims.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,0">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">⚠ Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Always work on copies of original light files. Saving a light file overwrites the file directly
                    unless you use Save As to create a new copy.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
